article.description: Ivory Latta scored 17 of her 22 points in the second half and North Carolina (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) used two big runs to defeat Virginia 76-56.
article.headline: Heels get 5th straight win vs. Cavs
article.linkText: UNC overcomes 12-point deficit to beat Virginia
article.story:
CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Virginia needed to have everything working to have a chance against North Carolina, and it did -- for eight minutes.

Then, with LaTonya Blue suffering through a 1-for-13 shooting performance and the Tar Heels starting to click, it was no contest.

Ivory Latta scored 17 of her 22 points in the second half and North Carolina (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) used runs of 16-0 and 11-0 after the break to beat the Cavaliers for the fifth consecutive time, 76-56 on Monday night.

"One-for-13. Wow. I don't know if she's ever had a game like that," North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell said of Blue, who averages nearly 13 points but whose only basket was a 3-pointer 6:26 into the game.

"We try a lot of different things out there (on defense) and we just keep trying things until we find something that works," Hatchell said. "Our team enjoys playing defense. They like to get after it."

The Tar Heels (19-3, 7-2 Atlantic Coast Conference) stumbled along early on but then started playing like one of the nation's best teams.

They closed to 29-27 at the break and then used the 16-0 run early in the second half run to turn a 39-33 deficit into a 49-39 lead.

"The second half, we just had to start to go and get it," said the 5-foot-6 Latta, who also had six assists, three steals and a block. "We got more aggressive on the defensive end and our offense started going."

Virginia (16-7, 5-4) got baskets from Kate Kreager and Tiffany Sardin to end the run and pull to 49-43. But the Tar Heels scored the next 11 points. The Cavaliers managed just one basket in the next eight minutes.

After taking the 39-33 lead, "it was sort of like the doors came off," Virginia coach Debbie Ryan said. "We just didn't get it done. We didn't execute on offense, and defensively we were a nightmare in the post."

The Cavaliers, on the verge of making the top 25 only a week ago, were humbled for the second game in a row. On Thursday night, they blew a 16-point second-half lead and lost 62-56 at North Carolina State.

"This is definitely gut-check time," Ryan told her team after the game. "We've got five games to go and you're only promised one after that."

The Tar Heels have no such concern, having won five straight.

Latta had just five points at halftime but had a 3 and a drive in the go-ahead burst and then kept the Tar Heels safely ahead. She was 11-for-12 from the foul line, where North Carolina outscored Virginia 22-4.

Camille Little added 17 points and Erlane Larkins 13 for North Carolina, which shot 49 percent and outrebounded Virginia 41-31. The Cavaliers had 19 turnovers leading to 21 North Carolina points.

Jocelyn Logan-Friend led Virginia with 13 points, Takisha Granberry added 11 and Brandi Teamer 10. But Logan-Friend and Teamer were two of the chief culprits in a slew of easy inside shots the Cavaliers missed.

Virginia finished 23-for-66 from the field, 34.8 percent.
